RAW ENTERTAINMENT LOOKING FOR INVESTORS (Contributed by Tony Belding)
---------------------------------------

A couple of weeks ago, Troy Silvey posted a message here about RAW
Entertainment looking for investors.  They are looking for $5,000 to $20,000
to carry them through three or four months until the magazine reviews of
their new games hit the streets.

A couple of days ago I phoned John Ingram, the president of the company, and
spoke with him at some length.  He said it would be fine if some wealthy
person were to offer up a $20,000 lump, but what he really hoped for was to
find more like 40 people who could each kick in $500.

In case you missed the earlier message, the plan is to repay the investment
plus 20% based on sales.  For example, a $1,000 investment would return
$1,200, payable when 1,200 games have been sold.  That should be in about
6-9 months, so you're looking at something like 30%-40% APR return there.

RAW Entertainment has been publishing wargames for the Amiga and PC for
quite a while now.  John said he does not expect much continuing sales from
their old titles, though.  They need to get the new stuff out.  He told me
RAW Entertainment is the only company left doing wargames for the Amiga.  As
far as I can tell, he's right.  If RAW Entertainment goes under, that's the
end of strategy wargames for us.

Now, here is what really got to me.  I waited a couple of weeks after the
original post appeared here before I called.  John told me how many other
people had called about that notice.  Zero.  Zip.  Nada.  Yes, I was the
only one who gave them a ring, the only one who expressed any interest at
all.

It's always been my experience here on FidoNet that people will talk about
doing a lot of things, but 9 times out of 10 it's just talk and no action. 
People here talk about supporting the Amiga.  What do they really DO to
support the Amiga?

Okay, I know most people here are not independently wealthy.  But there's
got to be a few this echo who could kick in $500!  I listened as John
explained his position at some length, and he struck me as highly
knowledgable and concerned about the Amiga marketplace.  I believe he knows
his business.  Don't take my word for it!  Give him a ring and chat with
him; form your own opinion!

I plan to put my money into this.  I haven't decided how much yet, but I
will participate.  I hope some others here will at least look into it.  That
number is (713) 286-2386.

